    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p><bibl><ptr target="#gasparini-rosamilia2016"/>, n. <citedRange>13</citedRange> (fig. 27)</bibl>, whence
                <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>66.2341</citedRange></bibl>;
                <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>134500</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><orig><choice><unclear>η</unclear><unclear>ι</unclear></choice><choice><unclear>ρ</unclear><unclear>γ</unclear></choice><unclear>ι</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Ξην_"><seg part="I">Ξη<supplied reason="lost">ν</supplied></seg><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name></persName> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Xèn<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Xen<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Xen<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>This poor fragment of what seems to be a monumental piece, perhaps an architrave, is difficult to interpret. E. Rosamilia shows that at line 2 there is no other 
               possibility than the beginning of a personal name in <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ξην(ο)-</foreign> or its common short form <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ξῆνις</foreign>.
               If so, line 1 should also contain a personal name and the combination of all possibilities leads him to three already attested names: <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ιγισαν</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ἠρίλοχος</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ἠρίνοος</foreign>. It is impossible to push this further. 
                   On the whole, the inscription might be the dedication of a monument.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
